\title{A Surgical LaTeX Editor Agent}

\begin{document}

\begin{abstract}
We present a backend agent that parses LaTeX papers into structural zones
and edits individual sections under natural-language instructions.
\end{abstract}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
Academic writing in LaTeX is a slow, error-prone craft. Authors spend
significant effort rephrasing sections, tightening prose, and reconciling
citations across drafts. Existing editors help with syntax but offer little
semantic assistance \cite{Knuth1984Literate, Lamport1994LaTeX}.
In this paper we present a backend agent that parses LaTeX papers into
structural zones and lets the user rewrite individual sections through
natural-language instructions, with surgical edits that never touch the
surrounding document.

\section{Background}
The development of a LaTeX-section-level editor relies on a methodology that combines zone and section parsing to identify and isolate specific sections of a document. This approach enables the editor to focus on rewriting individual sections based on user instructions, leveraging the power of Groq for instruction-driven rewrites. By parsing the document into distinct zones and sections, the editor can accurately identify the context and scope of the rewrite operation, ensuring that changes are applied correctly and efficiently. This methodology is rooted in the principles of literate programming, as described by Knuth \cite{Knuth1984Literate}, which emphasizes the importance of clear and readable code. By applying these principles to LaTeX editing, our editor aims to provide a more intuitive and effective way to manage and revise complex documents.

\subsection{Editors}
Existing LaTeX editors focus on syntax, not semantics.

